00:19:08.613 --> 00:19:12.970
Wait a minute. I can't tomorrow. I gotta
meet Finestein and the set designer.

240
00:19:13.133 --> 00:19:15.283
Either we talk now
or we wait six months.

241
00:19:15.453 --> 00:19:18.923
- What's with your tie? Is that your tie?
- Yeah. why?

242
00:19:19.093 --> 00:19:21.653
I don't know. It's tied funny.

243
00:19:22.853 --> 00:19:26.050
You wouldn't wanna risk patching
things up. Gloria. Save our marriage.

244
00:19:26.213 --> 00:19:27.248
Gloria?

245
00:19:28.573 --> 00:19:30.165
- No. no.
- He called you tu. not vous.

246
00:19:30.333 --> 00:19:33.564
- We're standing in front of my class.
- We're not having a conversation?

247
00:19:33.733 --> 00:19:37.442
- Oh. please. Ivan. Please.
- We're having a beginner's conversation?

248
00:19:40.013 --> 00:19:42.208
You're not coming home again tonight.

249
00:19:42.373 --> 00:19:45.206
- I'm not sure.
- What does that mean?

250
00:19:46.373 --> 00:19:49.126
- No.
- You hear that? "No."

251
00:19:51.893 --> 00:19:55.681
No. no. Iv�n. l'm not leaving you
for another man.

252
00:19:55.853 --> 00:19:57.844
Larry? He's not a man?
He's a duck?

253
00:19:58.013 --> 00:20:03.133
Larry is an intimate friend whose life
is faltering slightly who needs me.

254
00:20:03.293 --> 00:20:05.363
You have your show.
You don't need me.

255
00:20:05.533 --> 00:20:08.445
- Gloria. what are you doing to us?
- Iv�n.

256
00:20:08.653 --> 00:20:11.486
- What are you doing to us?
- Iv�n. l'm hurting you.

257
00:20:11.653 --> 00:20:14.121
That's the kindest thing
you've said in a month.

258
00:20:14.293 --> 00:20:15.567
"Lvan. l'm hurting you."

259
00:20:15.773 --> 00:20:18.765
Lvan. I don't want to
grow old with you.

260
00:20:19.373 --> 00:20:21.329
I see we're finished with kindness.

261
00:20:21.493 --> 00:20:24.610
We're now moving to hatefulness
and heartbreak.

262
00:20:26.813 --> 00:20:28.485
Well.

263
00:20:30.893 --> 00:20:32.485
- Where are you gonna be?
- Gloucester.

264
00:20:32.653 --> 00:20:34.211
- Not for me. For the kids.
- It's in Massachusetts.

265
00:20:34.373 --> 00:20:38.651
I know. I know! I'll write out
the number. Larry has a house there.

266
00:20:38.813 --> 00:20:41.373
- In Gloucester?
- Yes. in Gloucester.

267
00:20:41.533 --> 00:20:43.489
That's great. The sea.

268
00:20:45.293 --> 00:20:47.170
- You're sick. Gloria.
- I'm sick?

269
00:20:47.333 --> 00:20:48.322
Yeah. You're sick.

270
00:20:48.493 --> 00:20:50.723
You can't commit to a man.
to your children.

271
00:20:50.893 --> 00:20:52.042
I can't commit to a man?

272
00:20:52.213 --> 00:20:55.364
You'd abandon your clothing
if it made a demand of you.

273
00:20:55.533 --> 00:20:57.205
What are you talking about?

274
00:20:57.613 --> 00:20:59.729
Gloria. I have tried with you.

275
00:20:59.893 --> 00:21:03.203
I have been faithful. I have been loving.
I have been caring.

276
00:21:03.413 --> 00:21:05.722
You have been none of those things!

277
00:21:05.893 --> 00:21:07.963
You're at the typewriter
14 hours a day!

278
00:21:08.173 --> 00:21:11.131
I'm at the typewriter
because l'm a goddamn writer!

279
00:21:11.333 --> 00:21:13.688
I'm lonely. Ivan!

280
00:21:14.093 --> 00:21:16.653
Class dismissed.

281
00:21:19.893 --> 00:21:21.963
This isn't like Travalian to be late.

282
00:21:22.133 --> 00:21:25.921
Not to worry. this gives us
a chance to get the play read.

283
00:21:26.093 --> 00:21:27.685
You put up all that money?

284
00:21:27.853 --> 00:21:31.289
Any play with Alice Detroit
in the lead doesn't have to be read.

285
00:21:31.453 --> 00:21:34.490
Pretend that you read
the play. He's a little high-strung.

286
00:21:34.653 --> 00:21:36.564
We love his play.
Love it!

287
00:21:36.733 --> 00:21:38.212
What's he looking for?

288
00:21:38.493 --> 00:21:39.926
There's nobody here but us.

289
00:21:40.373 --> 00:21:42.933
Travalian! Here.

290
00:21:43.853 --> 00:21:46.526
I'm sorry l'm a little late.
How late am I?

291
00:21:46.693 --> 00:21:48.888
- Two hours and 10 minutes.
- Oh. my God.

292
00:21:49.053 --> 00:21:51.009
- I'm Ivan Travalian.
- Hi. how are you?

293
00:21:51.173 --> 00:21:52.925
- Hi.
- Who are you guys?

294
00:21:53.093 --> 00:21:55.846
"Who are you guys?" Kidding.
The Dickers.

295
00:21:56.013 --> 00:21:58.368
- He's Patrick.
- He's Jackie.

296
00:21:58.533 --> 00:21:59.807
The Dickers. Ivan.

297
00:21:59.973 --> 00:22:02.043
You have the Dickers.
you have greatness.

298
00:22:02.213 --> 00:22:04.443
There is no better accountant
than Jackie.

299
00:22:04.613 --> 00:22:07.207
- Am I right?
- He's the accountant. I'm the lawyer.

300
00:22:07.373 --> 00:22:09.682
See what you got?
One accountant. one lawyer.

301
00:22:09.853 --> 00:22:11.411
Born for business greatness.

302
00:22:11.613 --> 00:22:14.969
- We're backing you with 1.3 million.
- Our own money.

303
00:22:15.133 --> 00:22:17.363
That much? It costs that much?

304
00:22:17.533 --> 00:22:21.082
That's cheap. That's because
Arnold Kreplich is a superb producer.

305
00:22:21.253 --> 00:22:24.370
- Mr. Broadway.
- Come on. you're embarrassing me.

306
00:22:24.613 --> 00:22:27.411
You've attracted a star
in Alice Detroit for the lead.

307
00:22:27.573 --> 00:22:30.212
- Money in the bank.
- We're probably talking Tonys.

308
00:22:30.853 --> 00:22:34.482
Iv�n and I are gonna meet her.
have a drink. clean up a few things.

309
00:22:34.693 --> 00:22:36.763
- I thought she was all set.
- Trouble?

310
00:22:37.053 --> 00:22:39.283
- Are you kidding?
- You guys ought to know...

311
00:22:39.453 --> 00:22:41.364
...my wife. Gloria...

312
00:22:41.533 --> 00:22:43.922
...is having an affair
with an accountant...

313
00:22:44.093 --> 00:22:46.402
...named Larry Kotzwinkle.
- Do we know him?

314
00:22:46.573 --> 00:22:50.168
We know lzzy Kotzwinkle. but he's
kind of old. How old is Larry?

315
00:22:51.293 --> 00:22:52.885
Forties. Late 40's.

316
00:22:53.093 --> 00:22:55.209
Oh. God. no.
Izzy must be 80 by now.

317
00:22:55.813 --> 00:22:58.532
Why do you want to bring
that up at a business lunch?

318
00:22:58.693 --> 00:23:00.251
I'm so depressed.

319
00:23:01.573 --> 00:23:03.245
Playwright.

320
00:23:05.333 --> 00:23:08.052
I see it as a historic event.

321
00:23:08.213 --> 00:23:11.762
Two major talents meeting for
the first time. like Macy and Gimbel.

322
00:23:11.933 --> 00:23:13.207
What are you saying?

323
00:23:13.373 --> 00:23:16.365
- Macy and Gimbel. Come on!
- Arnold. don't talk crazy.

324
00:23:16.533 --> 00:23:17.807
I got a headache.

325
00:23:17.973 --> 00:23:20.168
Put your tie on. We gotta get going.

326
00:23:20.333 --> 00:23:22.767
I'm going in open-collar.
More Hollywood.

327
00:23:22.933 --> 00:23:24.571
We're doing theater.
Have your tie on!

328
00:23:25.933 --> 00:23:26.968
What?

329
00:23:27.133 --> 00:23:30.091
Miss Knoph. is that you?

330
00:23:30.933 --> 00:23:33.527
Sorry. Mr. Kreplich.
Did I knock too softly again?

331
00:23:33.693 --> 00:23:36.207
If you're gonna knock. knock!

332
00:23:36.413 --> 00:23:38.881
- I know. I know. I'm sorry.
- Well. what is it?

333
00:23:39.053 --> 00:23:42.489
Oh. yes! Sorry. There's a Mr. Handke
here to interview you...

334
00:23:42.653 --> 00:23:45.213
...from Voice of Broadway.
That's a program...

335
00:23:45.373 --> 00:23:48.729
...broadcast all over Europe from
Berlin for Armed Forces Radio.

336
00:23:48.893 --> 00:23:52.249
Ms. Knoph. we are going to The Plaza
to see Ms. Alice Detroit.

337
00:23:52.413 --> 00:23:54.085
He said you asked him to come.

338
00:23:54.253 --> 00:23:55.572
- Ms. Knoph.
- I'm sorry.

339
00:23:55.733 --> 00:23:56.927
Get rid of him.

340
00:23:58.253 --> 00:24:00.892
Okay. Travalian. let's go.

341
00:24:01.653 --> 00:24:05.009
There's one thing I forgot to tell
you about the meeting.

342
00:24:05.173 --> 00:24:07.164
It's nothing to get upset about...

343
00:24:07.333 --> 00:24:10.291
...but there's one detail
I forgot to work out.

344
00:24:11.293 --> 00:24:13.170
You're hugging me. Arnold. Why?

345
00:24:13.373 --> 00:24:14.522
Listen.

346
00:24:16.013 --> 00:24:17.446
- I lied.
- What?

347
00:24:17.613 --> 00:24:20.571
Alice Detroit has not agreed
to do the play.

348
00:24:23.773 --> 00:24:25.331
What?

349
00:24:25.613 --> 00:24:28.047
You told me she was signed
to do this play.

350
00:24:28.213 --> 00:24:31.569
You told the Post.
you told the Times. I read it.

351
00:24:31.773 --> 00:24:34.845
I did it for the good of the play.
You can convince her!

352
00:24:35.053 --> 00:24:38.807
You mean to tell me that you lied to me.
to everybody...

353
00:24:38.973 --> 00:24:41.203
...told them we had this superstar...

354
00:24:41.373 --> 00:24:42.852
...and we didn't?

355
00:24:43.013 --> 00:24:46.688
Now you want me to go
to the Palm Court and conv...

356
00:24:47.093 --> 00:24:49.607
- Where are you going?
- I'm gonna see my lawyer.

357
00:24:49.813 --> 00:24:52.281
- She's nearly convinced.
- You locked the door.

358
00:24:52.453 --> 00:24:55.365
- It's a piece of cake.
- Give me the key to the door.

359
00:24:56.333 --> 00:24:58.369
You threw the key out the window.

360
00:24:58.533 --> 00:25:01.127
Her lawyer says
she's 90 percent convinced!

361
00:25:01.293 --> 00:25:04.808
I don't need 90 percent. Arnold.
I need 100 percent.

362
00:25:04.973 --> 00:25:08.045
It's a whole person I need.
See. it's a demanding part.

363
00:25:08.213 --> 00:25:10.522
This is crazy. This is 51 stories.

364
00:25:10.693 --> 00:25:12.445
- Iv�n.
- You could kill somebody.

365
00:25:12.613 --> 00:25:14.649
All you've gotta do is chat with her.

366
00:25:14.813 --> 00:25:18.010
Be yourself. Be charming. be debonair
and you'll convince her.

367
00:25:18.173 --> 00:25:20.243
My wife left.
You want me to be charming?

368
00:25:20.413 --> 00:25:23.883
You wanna feed your orphanage?
If you don't convince Alice...

369
00:25:24.053 --> 00:25:28.331
...the Dickers will not give us the
1.3 million. under no circumstances!

370
00:25:28.493 --> 00:25:32.566
No ifs. no ands. no buts. no show!
Now. what do you wanna do?

371
00:25:47.813 --> 00:25:50.088
Ms. Detroit? Sorry we're late.

372
00:25:50.253 --> 00:25:52.164
- Iv�n Travalian.
- Oh. l'm so pleased.

373
00:25:52.333 --> 00:25:55.609
I am so thrilled.
I've read everything you've written.

374
00:25:55.973 --> 00:25:57.850
- This is Ivan Travalian.
- Oh. no.

375
00:25:58.013 --> 00:26:01.642
- I'm Arnold Kreplich. the producer.
- I blew it already. l'm sorry.

376
00:26:01.853 --> 00:26:05.641
- I should have known that.
I don't look like I write.

377
00:26:07.013 --> 00:26:08.890
- Couldn't you just die?
- Yes.

378
00:26:09.053 --> 00:26:10.884
- In what sense?
- The Plaza.

379
00:26:11.053 --> 00:26:14.090
- Vivaldi. violins. champagne.
- He loves The Plaza.

380
00:26:14.253 --> 00:26:16.164
Oh. I can see why. It's so beautiful.

381
00:26:17.893 --> 00:26:19.167
So...

382
00:26:20.413 --> 00:26:22.324
You live in California?

383
00:26:22.493 --> 00:26:24.245
Yes. absolutely. I love it.

384
00:26:24.413 --> 00:26:26.244
- You spend time there?
- He loves it.

385
00:26:26.413 --> 00:26:28.973
He does not love California. Arnold.

386
00:26:29.133 --> 00:26:30.771
You don't really care. do you?

387
00:26:30.933 --> 00:26:33.003
She's just making a little chit-chat.

388
00:26:33.173 --> 00:26:36.370
- Ms. Detroit. could I level with you?
- Yes. I wish you would.

389
00:26:36.573 --> 00:26:38.962
- This is no time to level.
- This man here...

390
00:26:39.133 --> 00:26:41.567
...was so anxious to have you
he lied to me.

391
00:26:41.733 --> 00:26:43.963
He told me you were doing the part.

392
00:26:45.013 --> 00:26:48.972
Now. I would love to sit and chat
with you. talk to you about my play...

393
00:26:49.293 --> 00:26:50.851
...if you were committed.

394
00:26:51.013 --> 00:26:53.846
No. I have not committed
to do your play.

395
00:26:58.773 --> 00:27:02.049
Well. I mean. I just feel a little
strange. you know.

396
00:27:02.213 --> 00:27:05.410
I mean. I don't feel like I can
sell my play to somebody else.

397
00:27:05.573 --> 00:27:08.531
Spent two years writing it.
I don't wanna be a salesman...

398
00:27:08.733 --> 00:27:10.325
But you don't have to sell it.

399
00:27:10.493 --> 00:27:13.371
I mean. your play is brilliant.
It sells itself.

400
00:27:13.573 --> 00:27:16.326
- It sells itself. did you hear that?
- I heard that.

401
00:27:18.653 --> 00:27:20.962
So do you want to do it or not?

402
00:27:21.533 --> 00:27:25.526
Okay. what l'd like to do is level
with you. all right?

403
00:27:26.493 --> 00:27:28.290
I'm scared.

404
00:27:28.453 --> 00:27:30.842
I don't know if I can do it.

405
00:27:31.013 --> 00:27:33.891
Mr. Travalian. I have never
worked on the stage.

406
00:27:34.053 --> 00:27:35.930
I work in movies.

407
00:27:36.253 --> 00:27:37.925
That's my business.
where I work.

408
00:27:38.093 --> 00:27:41.165
I don't know if I could carry a lead
in a Broadway show.

409
00:27:41.373 --> 00:27:43.887
I saw Sad Eyed Giris in the Park
three times.

410
00:27:44.053 --> 00:27:46.442
I know when an actress is right
for the part.

411
00:27:46.613 --> 00:27:49.173
- You're perfect for the part.
- Did you hear that?

412
00:27:49.373 --> 00:27:51.409
Yes. I heard that.

413
00:27:52.933 --> 00:27:55.527
- What are those pills?
- Aspirin. Why?

414
00:27:56.013 --> 00:27:58.083
Why did you ask me to do your play?

415
00:27:58.573 --> 00:28:01.087
The play I wrote is a serious play...

416
00:28:01.253 --> 00:28:03.813
...written in a comic mode. all right?

417
00:28:03.973 --> 00:28:07.966
It requires an actress that's gonna bring
intelligence and truth to it.

418
00:28:08.693 --> 00:28:10.649
But at the same time...

419
00:28:10.813 --> 00:28:13.725
...she has to be funny.
she has to act like a ditz.

420
00:28:13.933 --> 00:28:15.412
Ditz.

421
00:28:15.773 --> 00:28:19.812
Now. I know you haven't had much
stage experience. Ms. Detroit.

422
00:28:19.973 --> 00:28:23.727
You've had some and Morris Finestein's
the best director with actors.

423
00:28:23.933 --> 00:28:25.685
He's the best.

424
00:28:26.413 --> 00:28:30.042
He's... He'll work with you.
I'll be there.

425
00:28:30.533 --> 00:28:34.048
I don't know. I wouldn't be here
if I didn't think you could do it.

426
00:28:34.973 --> 00:28:37.248
Yeah. I've heard that about you.

427
00:28:40.173 --> 00:28:41.652
So?

428
00:28:42.933 --> 00:28:44.810
You wanna do it?

429
00:28:48.573 --> 00:28:51.007
Yeah. Yes.

430
00:28:51.213 --> 00:28:53.852
- You'll do it?
- Yes. Yes!

431
00:28:54.453 --> 00:28:55.932
Yes.
You'll do it?

432
00:28:56.133 --> 00:28:57.566
You'll do the play?

433
00:28:57.733 --> 00:28:59.724
Lvan. she'll do the play!

434
00:28:59.893 --> 00:29:02.771
You were wonderful!
You're wonderful.

435
00:29:02.933 --> 00:29:05.811
He's miserable. his wife is sleeping
with an accountant.

436
00:29:05.973 --> 00:29:08.692
It's a celebration! We got a star!

437
00:29:09.093 --> 00:29:11.561
- I gotta get the Dickers.
- Go ahead.

438
00:29:15.733 --> 00:29:18.964
Well. life is certainly great when
it works out. isn't it?

439
00:29:20.933 --> 00:29:24.767
- Would you like to make a toast?
- Oh. yeah.

440
00:29:25.893 --> 00:29:28.487
For the play. for you and me.

441
00:29:31.173 --> 00:29:33.562
Ms. Detroit. could I call you Alice?

442
00:29:37.013 --> 00:29:40.289
Alice. why do you take aspirin
with champagne?

443
00:29:40.493 --> 00:29:43.166
Oh. champagne gives me a headache.

444
00:29:47.853 --> 00:29:49.889
Geraldo. you're bagging garbage.

445
00:29:50.053 --> 00:29:52.362
I bagged the garbage two days
in a row now!

446
00:29:52.533 --> 00:29:54.330
Good. You're an expert. then.

447
00:29:54.493 --> 00:29:56.768
Iggy. you're washing.
Debbie. you're drying.

448
00:29:56.933 --> 00:29:59.049
- Spike?
- Eating.

449
00:29:59.453 --> 00:30:03.128
Mommy was ironing my lavender dress.
She must have taken it with her.

450
00:30:03.293 --> 00:30:06.251
- So wear another dress.
- That's the only dress that fits.

451
00:30:06.573 --> 00:30:08.529
So wear one that doesn't fit.

452
00:30:11.613 --> 00:30:16.368
Okay. we had breakfast. we're washing
dishes. we're bagging garbage.

453
00:30:16.533 --> 00:30:18.364
- We're surviving. right?
Not me.

454
00:30:18.533 --> 00:30:22.367
Yeah. we're doing beautifully. You
wanna clean the oatmeal out of this...

455
00:30:22.533 --> 00:30:25.172
...or should I just buy
another one for tomorrow?

456
00:30:25.333 --> 00:30:26.846
Can I ask you something?

457
00:30:27.013 --> 00:30:28.287
What?
Yeah.

458
00:30:28.493 --> 00:30:32.691
How come you never talk about your
mother. you never bring up her name?

459
00:30:33.773 --> 00:30:36.333
- It's a little weird.
- We talk about her.

460
00:30:36.893 --> 00:30:39.407
- Yeah. lots.
- Just not in front of you...

461
00:30:39.573 --> 00:30:41.165
...because it gets you crazy.

462
00:30:41.933 --> 00:30:43.685
- Oh. I see.
Hey.

463
00:30:43.893 --> 00:30:46.009
You figure she's moved out for good?

464
00:30:46.813 --> 00:30:49.088
No. Absolutely not.

465
00:30:49.293 --> 00:30:51.443
When she left my father.
it was for good.

466
00:30:51.653 --> 00:30:53.803
Yeah. my father too. Same thing.

467
00:30:54.013 --> 00:30:56.083
Same for us when she left our father.

468
00:30:56.253 --> 00:30:59.563
Old Gloria's got one undeniable
goddamn record. Pop.

469
00:30:59.733 --> 00:31:01.724
You can't knock her on consistency.

470
00:31:02.293 --> 00:31:05.569
- Well. those other times were different.
- Why?

471
00:31:10.253 --> 00:31:12.084
Isn't it time to hit the subway?

472
00:31:12.413 --> 00:31:17.009
- We're just trying to protect you.
- I know. I know.

473
00:31:19.133 --> 00:31:23.570
I haven't understood
one word of your babbling.

474
00:31:24.373 --> 00:31:26.443
